<docs>
   <doc for="PenStyle">
 <summary>
     Defines different styles that a pen can be created with.

 </summary>
 <seealso cref='Pen'/>
   </doc>
   <doc for="PenStyle.Dash">
 <summary>
     Pen style that consists of a series of dashed lines: --------
 </summary>
   </doc>
   <doc for="PenStyle.DashDot">
 <summary>
     Pen style that consists of a dash, followed by a dot: _ . _ . _ .
 </summary>
   </doc>
   <doc for="PenStyle.DashDotDot">
 <summary>
     Pen style that consists of a dash, followed by two dots:
     _ . . _ . . _ . .
 </summary>
   </doc>
   <doc for="PenStyle.Dot">
 <summary>
     Pen style that consists of a dotted line: ...........
 </summary>
   </doc>
   <doc for="PenStyle.InsideFrame">
 <summary>
    <para>
       This style creates a solid pen that is drawn from within any given
       bounding rectangle. Using this style allows you to have a wide pen that
       automatically conforms to the interior of a rectangle.
    </para>
 </summary>
   </doc>
   <doc for="PenStyle.Null">
 <summary>
     A "null" pen is a pen that doesn't draw at all.  This is useful when
     you have a function that always draws a border, but you don't want
     the border.
 </summary>
   </doc>
   <doc for="PenStyle.Solid">
 <summary>
     Pen style that consists of a solid line: ___________
 </summary>
   </doc>
   <doc for="PenStyle.Min">
 <summary>
    The minimum value for this enumeration.
 </summary>
   </doc>
   <doc for="PenStyle.Max">
 <summary>
    The maximum value for this enumeration.
 </summary>
   </doc>
</docs>

